> Personally, I think recommended level items (which you should be seeing more of these days) are a better solution to the twinking problem. If you're too low level, sure, you can have this AC 25 armor with +5 bonuses across the board and that gives you a 50% haste -- except, at your level, it's AC 6, has no bonuses, and doesn't give you any haste at all. This lets higher level characters still work on quests they may have missed, while simultaneously providing a viable reason for people not to give out high-end items like candy. <p>Illudin Arbitrator<br>Enchanter and Incorrigible Adventurer<br>Bringing together and calming Norrathians since 3174<br>"Onward, all, to our destinies! Adventure awaits!"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ujarkellraven.showPublicProfile?language=EN>JarkellRaven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 842<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/29/02 4:21:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2209.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Trivial loot code. friend or foe?</span><hr size=1> Personally, I love TLC, as it gives higher level people a reason to work with lower level people... the higher level person can trade something they have the power to get for something the lower level type can get.  Does it hurt sometimes?  Sure, cultural tradeskill items being the worst example.  But I think it does more good than harm.<br><br>Jarkell Ravensteel<br>Dawn Rising <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uayida.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayida</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 223<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/29/02 6:39:39 am)</font><br>   <